ğŸ§ Lesson 03 â€“ Linux Core Concepts (Overview)
1. The Linux Filesystem

Everything is a file (even devices, processes).

Directory structure starts at / (root).

Important directories:

/home â†’ user files

/etc â†’ system configs

/var â†’ variable data (logs, spool files)

/bin & /usr/bin â†’ essential binaries/commands

/tmp â†’ temporary files

2. Users & Groups

Every process runs as a user.

Users belong to one or more groups.

Commands:

whoami â†’ show current user

id â†’ show user ID and groups

groups â†’ list groups

3. Permissions

Each file has permissions: read (r), write (w), execute (x)

For three categories:

Owner

Group

Others

Example from ls -l:

-rw-r--r--  1 user group  120 Sep 30 file.txt


Change with chmod (symbolic or numeric).

4. Processes

A process = a running program.

ps aux â†’ list processes.

top or htop â†’ live view of CPU/memory usage.

kill PID â†’ stop a process.

5. Package Management

Install/remove software.

Depends on distro:

Debian/Ubuntu: apt (apt update, apt install)

Red Hat/CentOS: yum or dnf

Example:

sudo apt install nano


âœ¨ These are the â€œcore building blocksâ€ â€” how Linux is organized, how users/permissions work, how processes run, and how software is managed.

