ğŸ§ Lesson 03 â€“ Linux Core Concepts
1. The Linux Filesystem

Linux is organized like a tree ğŸŒ³.

The very top is / (root).

Everything in Linux is a file (folders, devices, even running processes).

Important directories:

/home â†’ your personal stuff (each user has a folder here).

/etc â†’ system settings/configuration files.

/var â†’ changing stuff like logs (/var/log/).

/bin and /usr/bin â†’ essential programs/commands.

/tmp â†’ temporary files (auto-cleaned sometimes).

ğŸ‘‰ Think of / as the trunk of a tree, and everything else are branches.

2. Users & Groups

Linux is multi-user â†’ many users can exist on the same system.

Each user belongs to at least one group.

Groups make permissions easier (e.g., all admins in the sudo group).

Commands:

whoami â†’ shows your username.

id â†’ shows user ID, group ID, and groups.

groups â†’ lists the groups you belong to.

3. Permissions

Every file has permissions for three categories:

Owner (the user who owns the file).

Group (users in the same group).

Others (everyone else).

Permissions:

r = read

w = write

x = execute (run as a program/script)

Example:
-rw-r--r--  1 user group  120 Sep 30 file.txt


Owner = rw- (read + write)

Group = r-- (read only)

Others = r-- (read only)

Change permissions:

Symbolic: chmod u+x script.sh (add execute for user).

Numeric: chmod 755 script.sh

7 = rwx

5 = r-x

4. Processes

A process = a running program.

Every process has a PID (process ID).

Commands:

ps aux â†’ show processes.

top (or htop) â†’ live view of CPU/memory usage.

kill PID â†’ stop a process.

5. Package Management

Linux needs a way to install/remove software.
It depends on the distribution:

Debian/Ubuntu â†’ apt

sudo apt update
sudo apt install nano


Red Hat/CentOS â†’ yum or dnf

sudo yum install nano

